## What happened

`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because Apple's **Security.framework** dropped DSA support. In earlier .NET versions macOS could still use an OpenSSL-based backend, but .NET 11 removed that fallback path, making DSA unconditionally unsupported on macOS.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), switch to a managed, cross-platform implementation like **BouncyCastle**:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the platform-dependent code:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — throws on macOS in .NET 11
using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyParams);
bool ok = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);

// ✅ After — works everywhere (managed code, no OS dependency)
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var pubKey = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(
    legacyParams.Y,                         // public key value
    new DsaParameters(legacyParams.P, legacyParams.Q, legacyParams.G));

var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool ok = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

> **Note:** `BigInteger` values in BouncyCastle are constructed from the byte arrays in `DSAParameters` — use `new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.Y)` etc.

### Other options

| Approach | Trade-off |
|---|---|
| **BouncyCastle** (recommended) | Pure managed code; works on all platforms |
| Ship your own OpenSSL via P/Invoke | Complex packaging & maintenance burden |
| Restrict to Linux/Windows only | Drops macOS support |
| Re-sign data with ECDSA/RSA | Requires a one-time migration step |

For new signatures, migrate to **ECDSA** or **RSA** — DSA is deprecated industry-wide.
